The user is first prompted for her old password if one is present. This password is then hashed (encrypted) and compared against the stored password in the /etc/shadow. The user has only one chance to enter the correct password.
The super user is permitted to bypass this step so that forgotten passwords may be changed. A new password is tested for complexity. As a general guideline, passwords should consist of 10 to 20 characters including one or more from each of following sets:The user is first prompted for her old password if one is present. This password is then hashed (encrypted) and compared against the stored password in the /etc/shadow. The user has only one chance to enter the correct password.
